\section{The classical paths: fluctons}  \label{sec_flucton}
For pedagogical reasons, we will proceed using particular examples, for which
expressions can be simple enough to allow analytic evaluation of all quantities.
In what follows we will set units such that $\omega=1$, or $\eta=1/\sqrt{8\lambda}$, so that there remains only one parameter of the problem, $\lambda$. It would also be useful to shift the coordinate $x(\tau)=y(\tau)+\eta$.


It is hard not to start with the harmonic oscillator, as the first example.
 One can always select units in which the particle  mass $m=1$ and the
oscillator frequency $\omega=1$, so that our Lagrangian is written as
\begin{eqnarray} L_E={\dot{x}(\tau)^2 \over 2}+  {x(\tau)^2 \over 2} \end{eqnarray}
Note that, for positivity, the Euclidean sign change we apply not to the kinetic, but to the potential term.
Anyway, in time $\tau$ the oscillator does not oscillate but relaxes,  classical EOM produce solutions of the kind
$e^\tau,e^{-\tau}$. The flucton solution

on a circle with circumference $\beta$ can be easily found as their superposition
satisfying $x(0)=x(\beta)=x_0$, namely
\begin{eqnarray} x_{flucton}(\tau)={ x_0 \over 1 + e^\beta}  \left( e^{\beta - \tau}  +
 e^\tau
\right) \end{eqnarray}
At low $T$ it is simply $x_0 e^{-| \tau |}$, and at high $T$ or small circle it can be just approximated by  $x_0$. An example is shown in Fig.\ref{fig_fluct}(a).

The  classical action of such a path is
\begin{eqnarray} S_{flucton}=x_0^2 \tanh\bigg({\beta \over 2}\bigg) \end{eqnarray}
it tells us that the particle distribution  \begin{eqnarray} P(x_0)\sim exp\left(- {x_0^2 \over  \coth ({\beta \over 2})}\right) \end{eqnarray}
is Gaussian at any temperature. Note furthermore, that the width of the distribution
\begin{eqnarray}
 <x^2>=(1/2)\coth \bigg({\beta \over 2}\bigg)={1 \over 2}+ {1 \over e^\beta -1}
\end{eqnarray}
can be recognized as zero-point plus thermal number of quanta excited. These results
are of course very well known, see e.g. Feynman's Statistical Mechanics \cite{Feynman_SM}.

Our next example is the symmetric power-like potential
\begin{eqnarray}
V={g^2 \over 2}  x^{2N}
\end{eqnarray}
for which the classical solution with the energy $E=0$
following from the (Euclidean) classical equation
$ -{\dot{y}^2\over 2}+V(y)=0
$
