with two degenerate minima. Tunneling between them is described by well known instanton solution
\begin{eqnarray}
 X_{inst}(\tau) \, = \, \eta\,\tanh(\frac{1}{2}\omega(\tau-\tau_c)) \label{instanton}
\end{eqnarray}
with $\omega^2=8\,\lambda\,\eta^2$.
We will discuss both the {\em weak coupling } limit of small $\lambda$, and the {\em strong coupling} limit
of large $\lambda$. In fact, the transition between them  happens when 
the instanton action $S[X_{inst}(t)]=1/12\lambda$ is larger or smaller than one.

Standard steps are selecting units for $\eta$ such that $\omega=1$ and shifting the coordinate by it,
\begin{eqnarray} x(\tau) = y(\tau) + \eta \end{eqnarray}
so that the potential takes the form
\begin{eqnarray} V={y(\tau)^2 \over 2} \left(1 + \sqrt{2\lambda} y(\tau) \right)^2 \end{eqnarray}
corresponding to standard harmonic oscillator at small $y$.

The {\em flucton} solution,   the minimal action path for the path integral (\ref{P}), in which the path is forced to pass through the point $x_0$ at $t=0$ at







 the zero $T$ case, or very large circle $\beta\rightarrow \infty$, now takes the form
\begin{eqnarray} y_{fluct}(\tau)={ x_0 \over
 e^{|\tau | }(1 + \sqrt{2} x_0 \sqrt{\lambda}) -
  \sqrt{2} x_0 \sqrt{\lambda}
 } \label{eqn_fluct}
\end{eqnarray}
with exponential decrease to large $| \tau |$. Its generalization to any $T$ is straightforward.

The action of this solution is
\begin{eqnarray} S[y_{fluct}]= x_0^2 (1 + 2 \sqrt{2\lambda} x_0/3) \end{eqnarray}
and thus in the leading semiclassical approximation the probability to find the particle at $x_0$ takes the form
\begin{eqnarray} P(x_0)\sim exp[-x_0^2  - {2 \sqrt{2\lambda} \over 3} x_0^3] \end{eqnarray}
In the weak coupling limit only the first term remains, corresponding to the Gaussian found state wave function of the harmonic
oscillator. In the strong coupling limit the second term is dominant, and the distribution then corresponds to
well known cubic dependence on the coordinate. These classical-order results
are of course the same as one gets from a standard WKB approximation.


When $|x_0|<\eta$ the classical solution now is made of pieces of the instanton solution.
\bigskip

Our last example is the {\em sine-Gordon potential}

with infinite number of degenerate vacua. Tunneling between adjacent vacua is described by well known instanton solution
 \begin{eqnarray} X_{inst}(t) \, = \,  \frac{4}{g} \arctan(e^{t})  \label{instantonSG}
 \end{eqnarray}
In the zero $T$ case, or very large circle $\beta\rightarrow \infty$, the flucton
solution has a very simple  form
\begin{eqnarray} y_{fluct}(\tau)\ =\ \frac{4\,\text{arccot}\bigg[ e^t\,\cot(g\,x_0/4)  \bigg]}{g}
\label{eqn_fluctSG}
\end{eqnarray}
The action of this solution is
\begin{eqnarray} S[y_{fluct}]= \frac{16\,\sin^2(g\,x_0/4)}{g^2} \end{eqnarray}
and thus in the leading semiclassical approximation the probability to find the particle at $x_0$ takes the form
\begin{eqnarray} P(x_0)\sim exp[-\frac{16\,\sin^2(g\,x_0/4)}{g^2}] \end{eqnarray}

\section{Fluctuations around the classical path} \label{sec_fluctuations}
Now we add quantum fluctuations around the classical path
\begin{eqnarray} y(\tau)=y_{classical}(\tau)+f(\tau) \end{eqnarray}
put this expression into the action and expand it to the needed order in $f$. But before we do so, let us remind the reader
that, by the definition, all paths should pass through the same point at $\tau=0$ and thus
there is an important condition $f(0)=0$.

Since the classical path is a local minimum, there is no term $O(f^1)$ in the action, except perhaps at time $\tau=0$.
The fluctuations are described by the Lagrangian
\begin{eqnarray}
  L={ \dot{f}(\tau )^2\over 2}+ V''(y_{fluct}) \frac{f(\tau)^2}{2} +O(f^3)
\end{eqnarray}
where we used a short hand notations $V''(y_{fluct})={\partial^2 V(y)/\partial y^2 }|_{y=y_{fluct}} $. Its variation leads to Schr\"{o}edinger-like equation
with the potential $V''$.

For harmonic oscillator this potential  $V''$ is just a constant,
 so in this case the fluctuations do not depend on the  classical path.
Higher order derivatives of $V$ all vanish, so in this case all
fluctuations are just Gaussian.

For quartic potential and the famous classical solution $X_{inst}(t)$ (\ref{instanton}), the $instanton$, the potential entering has the well known form
\begin{eqnarray}
 \frac{\partial^2 V(y)}{\partial y^2 }|_{y=y_{inst}}
  = \omega^2 \left(1 - {3 \over 2 \cosh^2(\omega \tau/2)} \right)  \label{inst_V"}
\end{eqnarray}
This potential is one of few exactly solvable quantum mechanical problems. There are two bound states, the famous zero mode with eigenvalue zero and another state with eigenvalue $3/4 \omega^2$, as well as the continuum
of unbound states with eigenvalue above $\omega^2$. Since one has the analytic expression for the scattering phase
$\delta_p$,  the determinant has been evaluated so to say ``by definition", using complete set of states, for a review see e.g.
\cite{Vainshtein:1981wh}. A new relation between the determinant and the Green function for the instanton  we will discuss
in section \ref{sec_sum_rule}.

In the case of flucton classical solution (\ref{eqn_fluct})
the potential of the fluctuations has the following form

