\end{eqnarray}




\section{The Green function of the fluctuations around the flucton solution \label{sec_GF}}
The procedure in general is an inversion of the operator (\ref{eqn_operator})
Unlike the instanton problem, in which the inversion is only possible in the subspace normal to the zero mode,
the problem we discuss now has no shift symmetry and thus no zero mode.
(This symmetry is killed by the boundary condition at the fixed moment, $f(\tau=0)=0$.)

The corresponding equation to be solved thus is
\begin{eqnarray} -{\partial^2 G(\tau_1,\tau_2) \over \partial \tau_1^2}+ {\partial^2 V(y) \over \partial y^2 }|_{y_{fluct}(\tau_1)} G (\tau_1,\tau_2) = \end{eqnarray}

The equation with zero r.h.s.  has two solutions


\begin{eqnarray} f_0(\tau)\ =\  \frac{e^{\tau}}{{(e^{\tau}(1+X)-X)}^2}   \end{eqnarray}

\begin{eqnarray} f_1(\tau)\ =\   \frac{e^{-\tau}}{2\,{(X-e^{\tau}\,(1+X))}^2} \end{eqnarray}

